3. Separate public deliverables from any future commercial operational layer.
4. Add named curator trials and an exit clause if subscriptions never materialize.

So: better than the prior proposal, much closer to the real governance problem, but it should stop short of replacing the RFC’s center of gravity entirely. The winning move is a hybrid: narrower public-good Phase 1, evidence-gated quantitative Phase 2, and a much harder boundary between commons infrastructure and paid operations.

